    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''China Blames Taiwan and U.S. for Military Tension in Region'' (news article, Oct. 17):</p>
        <p>Beijing's new white paper on national defense puts the blame for tensions in the Taiwan Strait on Taipei and the United States. In one stroke, it seems to have forgotten Taipei's consistent requests for peaceful talks, dismissed Taipei's many extended olive branches, and ignored Washington's desire to see cross-strait disputes settled without force.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''China Blames Taiwan and U.S. for Military Tension in Region'' (news article, Oct. 17):</p>
        <p>Beijing's new white paper on national defense puts the blame for tensions in the Taiwan Strait on Taipei and the United States. In one stroke, it seems to have forgotten Taipei's consistent requests for peaceful talks, dismissed Taipei's many extended olive branches, and ignored Washington's desire to see cross-strait disputes settled without force.</p>
        <p>The mainland's actions continue to belie the sincerity of its declarations. The white paper goes on to assert that the mainland is a peace-loving nation. Yet Beijing then turns around and tries to bully democratic Taipei with threats of violence. The Communists profess to have no desire to conquer other lands. Apparently, Taiwan just happens to be the one exception.</p>
        <p>FAN-PENG MENG  Deputy Dir., Information Division  Taipei Economic and Cultural Office  New York, Oct. 19, 2000</p>
      </block>
